{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476462"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:47:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:47:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13746"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13746"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.18,0.26,0.14,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55893"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6365"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41441"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1876"},{"type":"tags","id":"1932"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11840"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44171"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55893"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of fever, irritability, and decreased oral intake. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. On examination, he appears unwell with a temperature of 39.1\u00b0C, pulse rate 128/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. He has torticollis with limited range of motion of his neck. He is also noted to have inspiratory stridor. Oropharyngeal examination is unremarkable. A lateral neck radiograph is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Throat swab for group A streptococcus","Ultrasound of the neck","CT neck with contrast","MRI neck without contrast","Lumbar puncture"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child\u0027s presentation is concerning for retropharyngeal abscess, given his fever, irritability, decreased oral intake, torticollis, and inspiratory stridor. The lateral neck radiograph shows increased prevertebral soft tissue thickness, further supporting this diagnosis. The definitive next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003ECT of the neck with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E, which will demonstrate a hypodense fluid collection with rim enhancement in the retropharyngeal space, confirming the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Egroup A streptococcus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause retropharyngeal abscess, empiric antibiotics should be initiated to cover other common causative organisms including \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus \u003C/em\u003Eand anaerobes. A throat swab alone is not sufficient for diagnosis or management in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E has limited utility in evaluating retropharyngeal abscess due to poor penetration through air and bone. It is not the preferred imaging modality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E can diagnose retropharyngeal abscess but is not the first-line imaging study due to cost, time, and possible need for sedation in young children. It may be used if there is concern for intracranial extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough meningitis can present with fever and irritability, the presence of torticollis and stridor point towards a retropharyngeal infectious process rather than central nervous system infection. \u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated based on the child\u0027s current presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Retropharyngeal abscess can present with non-specific symptoms in young children, such as fever, irritability, and neck stiffness.","Lateral neck radiograph is often the initial imaging study for suspected retropharyngeal abscess, showing increased prevertebral soft tissue thickness.","CT with contrast is the definitive imaging modality to confirm retropharyngeal abscess, showing a hypodense fluid collection with rim enhancement in the retropharyngeal space."],"references":["Retropharyngeal Abscess. In: Wikicommons [online]. 2022. Available at: https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Retroabscess10.JPG","Wald ER. Retropharyngeal infections in children In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/retropharyngeal-infections-in-children","Torretta S, Ibba T, Guastella C, Gaini L, Di Cicco M, Folino F, et al. Management of upper retropharyngeal abscesses in children: Two case reports of a troublesome situation. Clin Case Rep. 2021 Oct 4;9(10):e04598. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8489505/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41441"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13746"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21094"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21094"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PrTTjLGhbWodGyiINaFUbzASdhg5wy.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PrTTjLGhbWodGyiINaFUbzASdhg5wy.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":987,"height":1197}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41441"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T14:44:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T14:45:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6365"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55893"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"G